derivation_new:
The transformations are derived by combining the \cref{Principle of relativity}{1.3} with the \cref{Constancy of the speed of light}{1.2}. Homogeneity of space and time implies that transformations between inertial coordinates are linear. The invariant light speed requires lightlike separations to remain lightlike in every inertial frame, and the stronger geometric statement is that the \cref{Spacetime interval}{3.2} is preserved: \[ ds^2=c^2dt^2-dx^2-dy^2-dz^2=c^2dt'^2-dx'^2-dy'^2-dz'^2. \] In four-vector notation, with \(x^\mu=(ct,x,y,z)\), a Lorentz transformation is written \[ x'^\mu=\Lambda^\mu{}_{
u}x^
u, \] and preservation of the \cref{Metric tensor}{3.1} gives the defining condition \[ \eta_{\alpha eta}\Lambda^\alpha{}_{\mu}\Lambda^ eta{}_{
u}=\eta_{\mu
u}, \qquad \eta_{\mu
u}=\mathrm{diag}(1,-1,-1,-1). \] For a boost with relative speed \(v\) along the \(x\)-axis, this gives \[ ct'=\gamma(ct- eta x), \qquad x'=\gamma(x- eta ct), \qquad y'=y, \qquad z'=z, \] where \( eta=v/c\) and \(\gamma=1/\sqrt{1- eta^2}\).

Starting from the \cref{Action principle}{5.2} with \cref{Minimal coupling}{8.3}, varying the charged particle worldline gives the covariant force equation \[  rac{dp^\mu}{d	au}=eF^\mu{}_{
u}U^
u, \] up to conventional placement of indices and unit factors. Here \(p^\mu\) is the \cref{Momentum four-vector}{4.5}, \(U^
u\) is the \cref{Velocity four-vector}{4.4}, and \(F^\mu{}_{
u}\) is formed from the \cref{Field tensor}{7.2}. In three-vector form this contains \[ \mathbf F=e(\mathbf E+\mathbf v	imes\mathbf B). \]
